<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step11_RealHttpCalls"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      Title="Step 11 - Real HTTP Calls">
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 11: Real HTTP Calls with HttpClient"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">REAL WORLD: Making actual HTTP requests with async/await.

HttpClient is .NET's built-in class for making web requests.
ALL its methods are async: GetAsync, PostAsync, GetStringAsync, etc.

This is THE most common real-world use of async/await: calling web APIs,
downloading files, sending data - all without freezing the UI.

Important HttpClient rules:
- Reuse ONE HttpClient instance (do not create a new one per request).
- All methods support CancellationToken.
- Always use "await" - never .Result or .Wait() on the UI thread!

Note: This step requires an internet connection.</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Fetch data from a public API"
                    Click="FetchApi_Click"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Fetch 3 APIs in parallel"
                    Click="FetchParallel_Click"/>

            <TextBox x:Name="Output" Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="300"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
